Things like that can be used to tell some amazing stories. The problem is that the people who write them are redditors, and therefore incapable of going in depth with concepts.
Take 'deathworlders' for instance. It's premise was everything that you are complaining about. Traits that humanity takes for granted, like our immune system, or adrenaline, ECT ECT are by alien standards, superpowers. We are the apex species of the universe by a mile, and nothing can compare to us. The only hindrance we have once we (steal and reverse engineer) FTL travel is our small population and simplistic technology.
Getting to the point where humanity became a player in the galactic game was done well in the story.
Where do you go from there? Lots of interesting ideas to choose from!
>Humanity defeats all threats, and conquers the universe. Human instinct demands more, and demands new struggles to overcome. Once more finding ourselves at the top, we turn on ourselves and nearly drive our own species to extinction, with the aliens powerless to stop the cyclical rise and fall of humanity. A statement on human nature!
>Humanity ascends to a key galactic player, but now the fledgling species has the moral obligation to act as peacekeepers. How will the fledgling species handle this new responsibility? Will we be tyrants? Saviors? Perhaps despite all our might, the galaxy is just to big of a place for us to defend, and we are forced to pick favorites? A statement on government and morality!
I'm sure I could think of more, but that's just off the top of my head.
Unfortunately, reddit brain made the author go
>"Oh shit, we're about to beat the bad guys! There can't be conflict without objectively evil bad guys who eat babies!"
And brought the plot to a screeching halt, now consisting of constant Mexican sex scenes and baseball games.
It's not the premise that sucks. It's the execution.

PERL is a scripting language, very popular in the UNIX/Linux world.

https://www.perl.org/

A "PERL script" is a program written in PERL. It's a very versatile language and one of the things for which it is very suited is manipulating and generating text.

https://www.elsewhere.org/pomo/ is an example of what a skilled individual can do with PERL. The web page has PERL code running on the back end. It randomly generates scholarly essays that are imitations/parodies of postmodernist literary criticism, for which there was an enormous fad in the 1990s. It's been online since 1996.
